body:
## Bug

The LSP server registers file watchers for `**/**/*.{ts,js}` and `**/controllers/**/*`, so VS Code correctly notifies the server when controller files are created, renamed, or deleted. However, the `onDidChangeWatchedFiles` handler in `server.ts` only acts on `.stimulus-lsp/config.json` changes and silently drops all other file change events:

```ts
connection.onDidChangeWatchedFiles((params) => {
  params.changes.forEach(async (event) => {
    if (event.uri.endsWith("/.stimulus-lsp/config.json")) {
      await service.refreshConfig()
      // ...
    }
    // ← JS/TS controller file changes are ignored entirely
  })
})
```

Because `service.refresh()` is never called when a controller file changes, the controller index goes stale. Adding, renaming, or deleting a controller has no effect on diagnostics or completions until the extension host is restarted.

## Steps to reproduce

1. Open a Rails + Stimulus project.
2. Reference a controller that doesn't exist yet in an ERB file. This creates an "invalid controller" diagnostic.
3. Create the corresponding controller file.
4. The diagnostic does not clear. The LSP still thinks the controller is missing.
5. Run `Developer: Restart Extension Host` → diagnostic goes away

## Expected behaviour

Creating, renaming, or deleting a controller file triggers `service.refresh()`, re-indexing the project so diagnostics, completions, and code lens update without a restart.

## Proposed fix

Add an `else` branch to call `service.refresh()` when a non-config file changes:

```ts
connection.onDidChangeWatchedFiles((params) => {
  params.changes.forEach(async (event) => {
    if (event.uri.endsWith("/.stimulus-lsp/config.json")) {
      await service.refreshConfig()
      service.documentService.getAll().forEach((document) => {
        service.diagnostics.refreshDocument(document)
      })
    } else {
      await service.refresh()
    }
  })
})
```

This mirrors the existing behaviour in `onDidChangeConfiguration`, which already calls `service.refresh()` on any configuration change.

I made this locally and it solved my issue. Happy to put in a PR for this.

## Environment

- stimulus-lsp v1.1.0
- VS Code 1.117.0

```js
import { Controller } from "@hotwired/stimulus"

export default class extends Controller {
  static targets = ["name"]

  connect() {
    this.nameTarget
//  ^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^ - Wrap the `this.nameTarget` accessor with an existential check, like: `if (this.hasNameTarget) { /* ... */ } `.
  }
}
```

We can also include a quick fix to rewrite the above to:

```js
import { Controller } from "@hotwired/stimulus"

export default class extends Controller {
  static targets = ["name"]

  connect() {
    if (this.hasNameTarget) {
      this.nameTarget
    }
  }
}
```

Inspired by @andrewmcodes on this [Remote Ruby Episode at 29:11](https://www.remoteruby.com/2260490/episodes/16696507-cyberpunk-vite-and-ruby-releases)

Currently Hotwire Native components aren't detected as Stimulus Controllers, even though they descend from the Stimulus Controller class.

Something like `bridge--button` at `app/javascript/controllers/bridge/button_controller.js` doesn't get detected:
```js
import { BridgeComponent, BridgeElement } from "@hotwired/hotwire-native-bridge"

export default class extends BridgeComponent {
  static component = "button"

  connect() {
    // ...
  }
}
```

Thanks to @yshmarov to catching this!

In a brand new Rails app with a single controller defined as so:

application.js
```
import "@hotwired/turbo-rails"
import "controllers"
```

controllers/application.js
```
import { Application } from "@hotwired/stimulus"

const application = Application.start()

// Configure Stimulus development experience
application.debug = false
window.Stimulus   = application

export { application }
```

controllers/books_controller.js
```
import { Controller } from "@hotwired/stimulus"

// Connects to data-controller="books"
export default class extends Controller {
  connect() {
  }

  favourite() {

  }
}
```

controllers/index.js
```
// Import and register all your controllers from the importmap under controllers/*

import { application } from "./application"

import BooksController from "./books_controller"
application.register("books", BooksController)
```

the suggested controllers when completing a `data-controller=""` attribute are `books`, repeated three times: 
![image](https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/6f4d10a4-f7b2-4474-8a87-b773ada178d7)

Update: It appears that the list of Registered Controllers in the Explorer panel also, after some time, updates to showing 3 Registered Controllers, when there's only 1 in the app.
